texts.label: text
texts.orig: My new ThinkPad arrived this week and it is working well! The Fedora 25 installation was easy and all of the hardware was recognized immediately.
texts.text: My new ThinkPad arrived this week and it is working well! The Fedora 25 installation was easy and all of the hardware was recognized immediately.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: However, there was a downside. The display looked washed out and had a strange tint. It seemed to be more pale than the previous ThinkPad. The default  ICC profile  in GNOME didn't help much.
texts.text: However, there was a downside. The display looked washed out and had a strange tint. It seemed to be more pale than the previous ThinkPad. The default  ICC profile  in GNOME didn't help much.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: There's a  helpful review over at NotebookCheck  that has a link to an  ICC profile generated  from a 4th generation ThinkPad X1 Carbon. This profile was marginally better than GNOME's default, but it still looked a bit more washed out than what it should be.
texts.text: There's a  helpful review over at NotebookCheck  that has a link to an  ICC profile generated  from a 4th generation ThinkPad X1 Carbon. This profile was marginally better than GNOME's default, but it still looked a bit more washed out than what it should be.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: I picked up a  ColorMunki Display  and went through a fast calibration in  GNOME's Color Manager . The low quality run finished in under 10 minutes and the improvement was definitely noticeable. Colors look much deeper and less washed out. The display looks  very  similar to the previous generation ThinkPad X1 Carbon.
